'''Hakken Shrine''' (Yatsurugi Jinja) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Yagami, Kuwabara-chō, {{ill|lt=Hashima City|Q819595|WD=Q819595|1=Hashima, Gifu}}, {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|WD=Q131277|1=Gifu Prefecture}}.

It is regarded as the tutelary shrine of {{ill|lt=Nakashima District (Gifu Prefecture)|Q24875402|WD=Q24875402|lt=Nakashima District|1=Nakashima district}} in {{ill|lt=Mino Province|Q864156|WD=Q864156|1=Mino Province}} (present-day southern Hashima City). In {{ill|lt=Kanpō|Q1145798|WD=Q1145798|1=Kanpō}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1743|Q7580|WD=Q7580|1=1743}}), thirty villages of Nakashima District in Mino Province became its parishioners<ref name="岐阜県神社庁"/>. ).

=== Overview ===
It is one of the candidate shrines (ronsha) for Ishikatana Shrine, an {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shrine Register|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} of {{ill|lt=Nakashima District|Q780420|WD=Q780420|1=Nakashima district}} in {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|WD=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}.

The place name of this area ({{ill|lt=Yagami Village|Q11391710|WD=Q11391710|lt=Yagami|1=Yagami}}) is derived from Hakken Shrine, and it is said to have been renamed from Ishida in {{ill|lt=Jōō|Q1145081|WD=Q1145081|1=Jōō (Edo period)}} 2 ({{ill|lt=1653|Q6965|WD=Q6965|1=1653}})<ref name="岐阜県神社庁"/>.

In {{ill|lt=1931|Q18782|WD=Q18782|1=1931}} (Shōwa 6), it became a gōsha {{Sfn|Hashima City|2004|p=663}}. On October 5, {{ill|lt=1960|Q3754|WD=Q3754|1=1960}} (Shōwa 35), it was designated a {{ill|lt=Kinpei-sha|Q119929592|WD=Q119929592|1=Kinpei-sha}} (No. Kin 54) by the Gifu Prefectural Association of Shinto Shrines {{sfn|Kimura|1997|p=83}}.

It shared a worship hall with Inari Shrine (enshrined deity: {{ill|WD=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama|Q3080728|WD=Q3080728|lt=Uka-no-Mitama-no-Kami|1=Ukanomitama}}; designated a {{ill|lt=Kinpei-sha|Q119929592|WD=Q119929592|lt=Ginpei-sha|1=Kinpei-sha}} by the Gifu Prefectural Association of Shinto Shrines<ref name="案内板">According to the on-site information board.</ref>{{sfn|Kimura|1997|p=83}}), and they existed as separate, independent shrines (Hakken Shrine on the east side and Inari Shrine on the west side). However, in {{ill|lt=2024|Q49619|WD=Q49619|1=2024}} (Reiwa 6) July, Inari Shrine was dissolved as a religious corporation and was merged into Hakken Shrine<ref name="法人番号">{{Cite web|ja|url=https://www.houjin-bangou.nta.go.jp/henkorireki-johoto.html?selHouzinNo=1200005003539|title=Information on Inari Shrine (National Tax Agency Corporate Number Publication Site)|format= |publisher=National Tax Agency|language=Japanese|accessdate=2025-07-19}}</ref>.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Ama-no-Iwato-wake-no-Kami|Q10940542|WD=Q10940542|lt=Kushiishimado-no-Mikoto|1=Ama-no-Iwato-wake no Kami}}
* {{ill|WD=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama|Q3080728|WD=Q3080728|lt=Uka-no-Mitama-no-Kami|1=Ukanomitama}}

=== History ===
Founded in {{ill|lt=Saikō|Q1324664|WD=Q1324664|1=Saikō}} 2 ({{ill|lt=855|Q25073|WD=Q25073|1=855}})<ref name="案内板"/><ref name="岐阜県神社庁">[https://www.gifu-jinjacho.jp/syosai.php?shrno=279 Hakken Shrine (Gifu Prefectural Association of Shinto Shrines)]</ref>. In Jōō 2 (1653), the Inari Shrine that had been worshipped by the {{ill|lt=Mōri clan (Minamoto lineage)|Q11547665|WD=Q11547665|lt=Mōri Genroku family|1=Mōri Genroku family}} of {{ill|lt=Ichinoeda Village|Q22124456|WD=Q22124456|1=Ichinoeda}} was merged into this shrine<ref name="案内板"/><ref name="岐阜県神社庁"/>.

=== Subsidiary shrines ===
* Wakamiya Shrine – transferred here in Jōō 2 (1653)<ref name="案内板"/>
* Shirahige Shrine
* Tado Shrine
* Fuji Asama Shrine
* Konpira Shrine, etc.

=== Access ===
* About a 5-minute walk from the “Yagami” bus stop on the southern route of the {{ill|lt=Hashima City Community Bus|Q11610099|WD=Q11610099|1=Hashima City Community Bus}}.

